    "# Meridian MMM Exercise: Pinewave Co.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Goal:** Build a Bayesian Marketing Mix Model using Google Meridian on 2 years of synthetic weekly data.  \n",
    "**Before starting:** Make sure you've run `python generate_data.py` to create `data/synthetic_mmm.csv`.\n",
    "\n",
    "Work through each section in order. Checkpoint questions are marked with **🔍 Reflect.**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Section 1: Load & Explore the Data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import matplotlib.dates as mdates\n",
    "\n",
    "df = pd.read_csv('data/synthetic_mmm.csv', parse_dates=['date'])\n",
    "print(df.shape)\n",
    "df.head()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "df.describe().round(2)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Plot revenue over time\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(14, 4))\n",
    "ax.plot(df['date'], df['revenue'], linewidth=1.5)\n",
    "ax.set_title('Pinewave Co. — Weekly Revenue')\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel('Revenue ($)')\n",
    "ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%Y-%m'))\n",
    "ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(mdates.MonthLocator(bymonth=[1, 4, 7, 10]))\n",
    "plt.xticks(rotation=45)\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Plot media spend by channel\n",
    "channels = ['tv_spend', 'search_spend', 'social_spend', 'display_spend']\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(4, 1, figsize=(14, 10), sharex=True)\n",
    "colors = ['#1f77b4', '#ff7f0e', '#2ca02c', '#d62728']\n",
    "\n",
    "for ax, ch, color in zip(axes, channels, colors):\n",
    "    ax.bar(df['date'], df[ch], width=5, color=color, alpha=0.7, label=ch)\n",
    "    ax.set_ylabel('Spend ($)')\n",
    "    ax.legend(loc='upper left')\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[-1].xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%Y-%m'))\n",
    "axes[-1].xaxis.set_major_locator(mdates.MonthLocator(bymonth=[1, 4, 7, 10]))\n",
    "plt.xticks(rotation=45)\n",
    "fig.suptitle('Weekly Media Spend by Channel', fontsize=13)\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Correlation: spend vs revenue (naive, without adstock)\n",
    "corr = df[['revenue'] + channels].corr()['revenue'].drop('revenue')\n",
    "print('Raw spend-revenue correlations (pre-adstock):')\n",
    "print(corr.round(3))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**🔍 Reflect — Section 1:**\n",
    "1. Do you see seasonality in revenue? Which quarters look strongest?\n",
    "2. Which channel has the highest raw correlation with revenue? Is that the channel you'd expect to have the highest ROI?\n",
    "3. TV has slow adstock decay (0.80) — meaning this week's TV spend still influences revenue several weeks later. Does a raw correlation capture that? Why or why not?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Section 2: Configure MeridianData\n",
    "\n",
    "Meridian requires data in a specific `xarray.Dataset` format via its `InputData` class."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": "import meridian\nfrom meridian.data import InputData\nfrom meridian.model import spec as model_spec\nimport tensorflow_probability as tfp\nimport xarray as xr\ntfd = tfp.distributions\n\nprint('Meridian version:', meridian.__version__)\n# If this fails, confirm you are inside the venv: source venv/bin/activate"
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": "# Meridian InputData uses named xarray DataArrays for all inputs.\n# Dimensions: geo (national=1), time (104 weeks), media_channel, control_variable\n\nmedia_channels = ['tv', 'search', 'social', 'display']\ncontrol_names  = ['price_index', 'holiday', 'trend']\ngeo            = ['national']\ntime_coords    = df['date'].dt.strftime('%Y-%m-%d').tolist()\n\n# Media spend: (geo, time, media_channel)\nmedia_array = xr.DataArray(\n    df[['tv_spend', 'search_spend', 'social_spend', 'display_spend']].values[np.newaxis],\n    dims=['geo', 'time', 'media_channel'],\n    coords={'geo': geo, 'time': time_coords, 'media_channel': media_channels},\n)\n\n# Controls: (geo, time, control_variable)\ncontrol_array = xr.DataArray(\n    df[control_names].values[np.newaxis],\n    dims=['geo', 'time', 'control_variable'],\n    coords={'geo': geo, 'time': time_coords, 'control_variable': control_names},\n)\n\n# KPI (revenue): (geo, time)\nkpi_array = xr.DataArray(\n    df['revenue'].values[np.newaxis],\n    dims=['geo', 'time'],\n    coords={'geo': geo, 'time': time_coords},\n)\n\n# Revenue per KPI unit = 1.0 because KPI is already in dollars\nrevenue_per_kpi = xr.DataArray(\n    np.ones((1, len(df))),\n    dims=['geo', 'time'],\n    coords={'geo': geo, 'time': time_coords},\n)\n\n# Build InputData\n# Note: parameter names may vary slightly by Meridian version — check docs if you get a TypeError\ninput_data = InputData(\n    kpi=kpi_array,\n    kpi_type='revenue',\n    media=media_array,\n    media_spends=media_array,   # media_spends (not media_spend) in v1.x\n    controls=control_array,\n    revenue_per_kpi=revenue_per_kpi,\n)\n\nprint('InputData configured successfully.')\nprint(f'  KPI shape:      {input_data.kpi.shape}')\nprint(f'  Media shape:    {input_data.media.shape}')\nprint(f'  Controls shape: {input_data.controls.shape}')"
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**🔍 Reflect — Section 2:**\n",
    "1. Why does Meridian use a `geo` dimension even for national data?\n",
    "2. What's the difference between `media` (impressions/GRPs) and `media_spend` (dollars)? In this exercise we use spend for both — what would change if you had actual impression data?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Section 3: Set Priors\n",
    "\n",
    "Priors encode your beliefs about parameter values before the model sees data. Meridian provides sensible defaults — start with those, then experiment in Section 7."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": "# Adstock prior: Beta distribution, mean ~0.5 (moderate decay)\nadstock_prior = tfd.Beta(concentration1=2.0, concentration0=2.0)\n\n# ROI prior: HalfNormal — ensures ROI > 0, most mass between 0–3x\n# scale=1.0 is a weakly informative default; adjust upward for high-ROI channels\nroi_prior = tfd.HalfNormal(scale=1.0)\n\nmodel_specification = model_spec.ModelSpec(\n    roi_prior=roi_prior,\n    adstock_prior=adstock_prior,\n)\n\nprint('Prior summary:')\nprint(f'  Adstock — Beta(2,2): mean={2/(2+2):.2f}, std={((2*2)/((2+2)**2*(2+2+1)))**0.5:.2f}')\nprint(f'  ROI — HalfNormal(1.0): most mass in [0, 3]')"
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Visualize the priors\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 4))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Adstock prior\n",
    "x_adstock = np.linspace(0, 1, 200)\n",
    "from scipy.stats import beta as beta_dist, halfnorm\n",
    "axes[0].plot(x_adstock, beta_dist.pdf(x_adstock, 2, 2), 'b-', linewidth=2)\n",
    "axes[0].set_title('Adstock Decay Prior — Beta(2,2)')\n",
    "axes[0].set_xlabel('Decay rate (0=instant, 1=permanent)')\n",
    "axes[0].set_ylabel('Density')\n",
    "axes[0].axvline(0.5, color='r', linestyle='--', label='mean=0.5')\n",
    "axes[0].legend()\n",
    "\n",
    "# ROI prior\n",
    "x_roi = np.linspace(0, 6, 200)\n",
    "axes[1].plot(x_roi, halfnorm.pdf(x_roi, scale=1.0), 'g-', linewidth=2)\n",
    "axes[1].set_title('ROI Prior — HalfNormal(scale=1.0)')\n",
    "axes[1].set_xlabel('ROI (revenue / spend)')\n",
    "axes[1].set_ylabel('Density')\n",
    "axes[1].axvline(1.0, color='r', linestyle='--', label='ROI=1x (breakeven)')\n",
    "axes[1].legend()\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**🔍 Reflect — Section 3:**\n",
    "1. The adstock prior is symmetric around 0.5. TV typically has slow decay (~0.8) and search has fast decay (~0.35). Is this prior appropriate, or should you set channel-specific priors?\n",
    "2. The ROI prior puts most mass below 3x. If you knew from past experience that Paid Search routinely delivers 5–8x ROI, how would you change the prior?\n",
    "3. What's the risk of using an overly tight (informative) prior?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Section 4: Fit the Model\n",
    "\n",
    "This section runs MCMC sampling. On CPU (MacBook), expect **10–25 minutes** for 4 chains × 500 samples.  \n",
    "Set `num_samples=200` for a faster (less accurate) run first, then rerun with 500 for the final result."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from meridian.model import Meridian\n",
    "\n",
    "mmm = Meridian(\n",
    "    input_data=input_data,\n",
    "    model_spec=model_specification,\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "print('Model initialized. Starting MCMC sampling...')\n",
    "print('This will take 10–25 minutes on CPU. Get a coffee ☕')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import time\n",
    "start = time.time()\n",
    "\n",
    "mmm.fit(\n",
    "    num_chains=4,\n",
    "    num_samples=500,     # reduce to 200 for a quick test run\n",
    "    num_warmup=500,\n",
    "    seed=42,\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "elapsed = time.time() - start\n",
    "print(f'\\nFitting complete in {elapsed/60:.1f} minutes.')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Section 5: Evaluate Convergence\n",
    "\n",
    "Before trusting model outputs, confirm the MCMC chains converged."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# R-hat diagnostic: values close to 1.0 mean chains mixed well\n",
    "# Target: R-hat < 1.1 for all parameters\n",
    "summary = mmm.get_rhat_summary()\n",
    "print('R-hat summary:')\n",
    "print(summary)\n",
    "\n",
    "max_rhat = summary['rhat'].max()\n",
    "if max_rhat < 1.1:\n",
    "    print(f'\\n✅ Max R-hat = {max_rhat:.3f} — convergence looks good!')\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    print(f'\\n⚠️  Max R-hat = {max_rhat:.3f} — some parameters did not converge.')\n",
    "    print('   Try increasing num_warmup to 1000 and rerunning Section 4.')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Trace plots: visualize chain mixing for ROI parameters\n",
    "mmm.plot_trace(var_names=['roi_m'])  # roi_m = media ROI parameters\n",
    "plt.suptitle('Trace Plots: ROI by Channel (all 4 chains)', y=1.02)\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Posterior predictive check: does the model reproduce the observed revenue?\n",
    "mmm.plot_posterior_predictive_check()\n",
    "plt.title('Posterior Predictive Check: Observed vs. Predicted Revenue')\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**🔍 Reflect — Section 5:**\n",
    "1. What does an R-hat of 1.0 mean? What would R-hat > 1.1 tell you?\n",
    "2. In the trace plots, do the chains look like 'fuzzy caterpillars' (good mixing) or do they drift apart (poor mixing)?\n",
    "3. In the posterior predictive check, does the model capture the seasonal peaks? Where does it miss most?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Section 6: Extract Results\n",
    "\n",
    "Now the interesting part: what does the model say about ROI, response curves, and budget?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# ROI by channel: posterior median + 90% credible interval\n",
    "roi_summary = mmm.get_roi_summary(confidence_level=0.90)\n",
    "print('ROI Summary (posterior median + 90% CI):')\n",
    "print(roi_summary.round(3))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Plot ROI with uncertainty\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(9, 5))\n",
    "\n",
    "channels_display = ['TV', 'Search', 'Social', 'Display']\n",
    "medians = roi_summary['roi_median'].values\n",
    "lo = roi_summary['roi_q05'].values\n",
    "hi = roi_summary['roi_q95'].values\n",
    "\n",
    "y_pos = np.arange(len(channels_display))\n",
    "ax.barh(y_pos, medians, xerr=[medians - lo, hi - medians],\n",
    "        color=['#1f77b4','#ff7f0e','#2ca02c','#d62728'],\n",
    "        alpha=0.7, capsize=5)\n",
    "ax.set_yticks(y_pos)\n",
    "ax.set_yticklabels(channels_display)\n",
    "ax.axvline(1.0, color='black', linestyle='--', label='Breakeven (1x)')\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('ROI (revenue per $1 spend)')\n",
    "ax.set_title('Estimated ROI by Channel (90% Credible Interval)')\n",
    "ax.legend()\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Revenue contribution decomposition\n",
    "decomp = mmm.get_contribution_summary()\n",
    "print('Revenue Contribution Breakdown:')\n",
    "print(decomp.round(2))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Response curves: shows diminishing returns\n",
    "mmm.plot_response_curves(\n",
    "    spend_multipliers=np.linspace(0, 3, 50),\n",
    "    confidence_level=0.80,\n",
    ")\n",
    "plt.suptitle('Response Curves: Marginal Revenue vs. Spend Level', y=1.02)\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Budget optimizer: given same total budget, what's the optimal allocation?\n",
    "total_budget = df[['tv_spend','search_spend','social_spend','display_spend']].sum().sum()\n",
    "print(f'Total budget to reallocate: ${total_budget:,.0f}')\n",
    "\n",
    "optimizer_result = mmm.optimize_budget(\n",
    "    total_budget=total_budget,\n",
    "    fixed_costs=None,\n",
    ")\n",
    "print('\\nOptimal budget allocation:')\n",
    "print(optimizer_result.round(2))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**🔍 Reflect — Section 6:**\n",
    "1. Which channel has the highest ROI? Does this match your intuition from the raw correlations in Section 1?\n",
    "2. Look at the credible intervals. Which channel's ROI estimate is most uncertain? Why might that be?\n",
    "3. The response curves show diminishing returns. For which channel does saturation kick in earliest?\n",
